Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE): This autoimmune disease can affect various organs, incluyendo el bazo, los pulmones y los riñones. Los principales sintomas incluyen exantema malar, fiebre, dolores musculares y articulares, y proteinuria.
Membranous glomerulonefritis: Esta condición es una causa frecuente de nefropatía por pérdida de proteínas. Los sintomas pueden ser leves, pero en algunos casos se puede presentar edema, cansancio, e proteinuria.
Lupus-associated nephropathy (LN) This condition involves a combination of the autoimmune features of Lupus with direct immune system damage of the kidneys. This overlap can lead to many of the same outcomes, such as proteinuria and edema, but can be further distinguished by a direct attack on glomerular structures.
Polyarteritis nodosa: Un trastorno que causa la inflamación y engrosamiento de las paredes de las arterias de pequeño y mediano tamaño, lo cual puede afectar diversos organos. Los sintomas incluyen exanthema, fiebre y dolores musculares y articulares.
Poststreptococcal glomerulonefritis (PSGN): Esta condición se presenta como consecuencia del proceso inflamatorio de una infección bacteriana, particularmente la faringitis o la escarlatina, y puede afectar los glomérulos de los riñones. Los sintomas incluyen fiebre, exanthema, edema, e proteinuria.
IgA Nephropathy (Berger’s Disease) This is a condition characterized by a buildup of IgA antibodies in the kidneys, leading to glomerular injury and inflammation. While the symptoms can be variable, many people will have blood and proteinuria, as well as potentially hematuria and elevated blood pressure. 
Henoch-Schönlein Purpura (HSP) An immune system issue causing blood vessel damage in small vessels of skin, joints, kidneys and intestines. It is marked in children by a typical skin rash on legs and buttocks. In adults it is often triggered by medication and can present as glomerulonephritis with hematuria, proteinuria and altered kidney functions. 
Polyangiitis with Microscopic Lesions: A rare autoimmune disorder characterized by vascular inflammation, especially of small vessels, leading to tissue injury. Initial presentation can include kidney damage and hematuria, proteinuria and elevated creatinine.
 Focal Segmental Glomerulosclerosis (FSGS) A primary cause of kidney disease that can lead to glomerular scarring. This can manifest with edema, hematuria, and nephrotic syndrome, including high protein levels in urine. 
 Anti-glomerular basement membrane (GBM) disease A rare autoimmune disorder characterized by the development of antibodies that attack and damage glomerular basement membrane, a structure crucial for filtering blood in the kidney, causing inflammation, hematuria and rapidly progressing kidney failure.
